cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: "Three Orthogonal Failure Axes in Hybrid AR / Diffusion Reasoning, with Trainable Fixes for Two of Them"
authors:
  - family-names: "Akbulut"
    given-names: "Eren"
abstract: >-
  Hybrid pipelines combining an autoregressive (AR) language model with
  a discrete-diffusion language model (DDLM) for chain-of-thought
  reasoning produce mixed results in the literature. We decompose the
  failure surface into three orthogonal axes -- interface-format
  brittleness, planner-content trust, and sampling-diversity
  preservation -- and characterize each independently on GSM8K with
  LLaDA-8B-Instruct and Qwen2.5-{0.5B,1.5B}-Instruct. (1) Interface
  brittleness is fixable with a small (r=8) prefix-robustness LoRA,
  with a measurable no-prefix-vs-cmaj capacity tradeoff. (2)
  Planner-content trust is non-monotonic in LoRA capacity: a 0.5B
  planner improves at higher capacity (+5pp); a 1.5B planner regresses
  by 13pp. (3) Sampling diversity is expanded, not collapsed, by
  format-augmented training (5/5-branch agreement 51.5% to 47.5%; mean
  unique answers per problem 1.825 to 2.07). Consensus distillation is
  design-sensitive, not architecture-limited: late-block answer-span
  surgery fails (c2c=70.5% across two iterations); earlier-block
  full-response surgery recovers (c2c=79.0%, within sampling error of
  the 80% pre-registered target). Block-coverage carries +4pp of the
  lift; full-response loss adds +2pp on top. Branch aggregation
  (cmajc) on the c2c-fixed model adds +3pp over base test cmaj,
  showing param-time and compute-time consensus mechanisms compose.
  A Qwen2.5-0.5B self-consistency baseline (b=5, t=0.7) reaches only
  40.5%, vs LLaDA cmaj 79-82%, ruling out generic self-consistency as
  the explanation for the diffusion advantage. All datasets and
  adapters are public on the Hugging Face Hub. Total compute: ~$3.50
  on 1 x RTX-4090.
version: 0.1.0
date-released: "2026-04-30"
url: "https://github.com/eren23/sfumato-paper"
type: software
keywords:
  - discrete diffusion language model
  - autoregressive language model
  - LoRA
  - hybrid reasoning
  - chain-of-thought
  - GSM8K
  - LLaDA
  - consensus distillation
